04729nam a22006855i 9780271087542DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710875427 a10.1515/97802710875422doi  a(DE-B1597)583726  a(OCoLC)1253313120  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPHO0110302bisacsh04a973.72231 aBest, Makeda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aElevate the Masses :bAlexander Gardner, Photography, and Democracy in Nineteenth-Century America /cMakeda Best. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b84 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction Elevate the Masses -- tChapter 1 The Fierce Flames of Democracy -- tChapter 2 Remove the Foul Blot -- tChapter 3 Labor's Portrait Gallery -- tChapter 4 Washington's Promise -- tConclusion: Convince the Understanding, Arouse the Conscience -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlexander Gardner is best known for his innovative photographic history of the Civil War. What is less known is the extent to which he was involved in the international workers' rights movement. Tying Gardner's photographic storytelling to his transatlantic reform activities, this book expands our understanding of Gardner's career and the work of his studio in Washington, DC, by situating his photographic production within the era's discourse on social and political reform.Drawing on previously unknown primary sources and original close readings, Makeda Best reveals how Gardner's activism in Scotland and photography in the United States shared an ideological foundation. She reads his Photographic Sketch Book of the War as a politically motivated project, rooted in Gardner's Chartist and Owenite beliefs, and illuminates how its treatment of slavery is primarily concerned with the harm that the institution posed to the United States' reputation as a model democracy. Best shows how, in his portraiture, Gardner celebrated Northern labor communities and elevated white immigrant workers, despite the industrialization that degraded them. She concludes with a discussion of Gardner's promotion of an American national infrastructure in which photographers and photography played an integral role.Original and compelling, this reconsideration of Gardner's work expands the contribution of Civil War photography beyond the immediate narrative of the war to comprehend its relation to the vigorous international debates about democracy, industrialization, and the rights of citizens. Scholars working at the intersection of photography, cultural history, and social reform in the nineteenth century on both sides of the Atlantic will find Best's work invaluable to their own research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aLabor movementzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveryzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aPhotography / Individual Photographers / Monographs.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311074521440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271087542zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271087542423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271087542.jpg  a978-3-11-074521-4  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPD